Below is a **single‑file, self‑contained** C‑binding for the hot‑path “walk every block and run user code”.  
It contains:

* a clean, `extern "C"` public API that a C programmer can include (`#include "blocksci_c.h"`);  
* an opaque iterator type (`bsci_iter_t`) that hides all C++ details;  
* a tiny `bsci_block_t` struct that carries the most‑useful block fields (you can extend it without breaking ABI);  
* a “run‑the‑whole‑collection” helper (`bsci_foreach_block`) that calls a user‑supplied C callback for each block;  
* a low‑overhead implementation – the callback is a plain C function pointer, no `std::function`, no virtual dispatch, no heap allocation, and the loop is a straight `for` over the native C++ iterator.  
* error handling that propagates C‑style `int` codes (0 = success, non‑zero = failure).  
* a small example at the bottom showing how a C program would use the API.

```c
/*=====================================================================
   blocksci_c.h   –  C bindings for BlockSci block iteration
   (single‑file, self‑contained; compile as C++ and link with libblocksci)

   Design goals
   -------------
   * 0‑overhead hot loop – the per‑block callback is a plain C function
     pointer that the C++ iterator calls directly.
   * Simple, stable ABI – only POD types and opaque pointers cross the
     language boundary.
   * Minimal dependencies – only <stddef.h>, <stdint.h>, and the
     BlockSci C++ headers.
   * Graceful error handling – all public functions return an int
     (0 = OK, >0 = error code).

   Usage from C
   -------------
   #include "blocksci_c.h"

   int my_cb(void *user, const bsci_block_t *blk) {
       /* do something cheap, e.g. count, accumulate, etc. */
       ++*(size_t*)user;
       return 0;               // 0 = keep iterating, non‑zero = abort early
   }

   size_t cnt = 0;
   int rc = bsci_foreach_block("/path/to/chain", &cnt, my_cb);
   if (rc) { ... }

=====================================================================*/

#ifndef BLOCKSCI_C_H
#define BLOCKSCI_C_H

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Public C API – pure C, can be included from any C compiler
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
#ifdef __cplusplus
extern "C" {
#endif

#include <stddef.h>   /* size_t   */
#include <stdint.h>   /* uint32_t, uint64_t */

/* Opaque iterator – the actual C++ iterator lives inside the implementation.
   Users never dereference it; it is only passed to destroy/advance functions. */
typedef struct bsci_iter_s bsci_iter_t;

/* A lightweight POD representation of a block.  Extend as needed – just keep
   it POD (no pointers, no C++ types) to stay ABI‑stable. */
typedef struct {
    uint32_t height;          /* block height (0 = genesis)                */
    uint64_t timestamp;       /* Unix epoch seconds                       */
    uint32_t tx_count;        /* number of transactions in the block       */
    uint64_t total_output;    /* sum of all output values (satoshis)       */
    /* Add more fields here if you need them – keep the struct POD. */
} bsci_block_t;

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Callback type – called for every block.
   Return 0 to continue, non‑zero to abort iteration early.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
typedef int (*bsci_block_cb_t)(void *user_data, const bsci_block_t *blk);

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   High‑level convenience API – walk the whole chain in one call.
   Returns 0 on success, >0 on error (or if the user callback aborts).
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
int bsci_foreach_block(const char *chain_path,
                       void *user_data,
                       bsci_block_cb_t cb);

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Low‑level iterator API – if you need more control (e.g. pause/resume).
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */

/* Create an iterator for the chain at `chain_path`.  On success returns 0
   and stores the newly allocated iterator in `*out`.  The iterator must
   later be destroyed with bsci_iter_destroy(). */
int bsci_iter_create(const char *chain_path, bsci_iter_t **out);

/* Destroy an iterator created by bsci_iter_create().  Safe to call with NULL. */
void bsci_iter_destroy(bsci_iter_t *it);

/* Advance the iterator by one block and invoke the user callback.
   Returns:
     0  – callback returned 0 and there are more blocks;
     1  – callback returned non‑zero (user asked to stop);
    -1  – iterator reached the end of the chain;
    >0  – error code (e.g. I/O failure). */
int bsci_iter_next(bsci_iter_t *it, void *user_data, bsci_block_cb_t cb);

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Optional helper: query the current block without advancing.
   Returns 0 on success, non‑zero if the iterator is at the end or on error.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
int bsci_iter_current(const bsci_iter_t *it,
                      bsci_block_t *out_block);

#ifdef __cplusplus
} /* extern "C" */
#endif

/* =====================================================================
   Implementation – C++ part (compiled as C++).
   ===================================================================== */
#ifdef __cplusplus
/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Include the real BlockSci headers.  Replace these includes with the
   actual ones from your BlockSci build.  The example uses placeholder
   names – adjust them to match your library.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
#include <blocksci/chain/chain.hpp>      // blocksci::Chain
#include <blocksci/chain/block.hpp>      // blocksci::Block
#include <blocksci/exception.hpp>        // blocksci::BlocksciError

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Internal opaque type definition.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
struct bsci_iter_s {
    /* The real iterator type from BlockSci.  We store both the chain
       (so we keep the underlying DB open) and the current iterator. */
    blocksci::Chain chain;                     // owns the DB
    blocksci::Chain::iterator cur;             // points to the next block
    blocksci::Chain::iterator end;             // sentinel
};

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Helper: translate a blocksci::Block into the POD bsci_block_t.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
static inline void fill_block_pod(const blocksci::Block &src, bsci_block_t *dst) {
    dst->height        = src.height();
    dst->timestamp     = src.timestamp();
    dst->tx_count      = static_cast<uint32_t>(src.tx_count());
    dst->total_output  = src.total_output();   // already satoshis (uint64_t)
    /* If you need more fields, add them here, keeping the POD rule. */
}

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Public API implementation
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
int bsci_iter_create(const char *chain_path, bsci_iter_t **out) {
    if (!chain_path || !out) return 1;               // invalid arguments
    try {
        bsci_iter_t *it = new bsci_iter_t;
        it->chain = blocksci::Chain(chain_path);    // may throw
        it->cur   = it->chain.begin();
        it->end   = it->chain.end();
        *out = it;
        return 0;
    } catch (const blocksci::BlocksciError &e) {
        (void)e;                                     // silence unused warning
        return 2;                                    // chain open failure
    } catch (...) {
        return 3;                                    // unknown failure
    }
}

void bsci_iter_destroy(bsci_iter_t *it) {
    delete it;   // safe even if it == nullptr
}

/* Return codes:
   0  – callback returned 0 and we have more blocks;
   1  – callback asked to stop (non‑zero return);
  -1  – iterator already at end;
   >0 – error opening/reading next block.
*/
int bsci_iter_next(bsci_iter_t *it, void *user_data, bsci_block_cb_t cb) {
    if (!it) return 1;
    if (it->cur == it->end) return -1;   // nothing left

    try {
        const blocksci::Block &blk = *it->cur;
        bsci_block_t pod;
        fill_block_pod(blk, &pod);

        int cb_rc = cb(user_data, &pod);
        ++it->cur;                       // advance regardless of cb result

        if (cb_rc != 0) return 1;        // user asked to abort
        return 0;                        // ok, continue
    } catch (const blocksci::BlocksciError &) {
        return 2;                        // read error
    } catch (...) {
        return 3;                        // unknown error
    }
}

/* Query the block that the iterator currently points to (without advancing). */
int bsci_iter_current(const bsci_iter_t *it, bsci_block_t *out_block) {
    if (!it || !out_block) return 1;
    if (it->cur == it->end) return -1;
    try {
        const blocksci::Block &blk = *it->cur;
        fill_block_pod(blk, out_block);
        return 0;
    } catch (const blocksci::BlocksciError &) {
        return 2;
    } catch (...) {
        return 3;
    }
}

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   High‑level convenience helper – walks the whole chain in one tight loop.
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
int bsci_foreach_block(const char *chain_path,
                       void *user_data,
                       bsci_block_cb_t cb) {
    if (!chain_path || !cb) return 1;

    try {
        blocksci::Chain chain(chain_path);          // may throw
        for (auto it = chain.begin(); it != chain.end(); ++it) {
            bsci_block_t pod;
            fill_block_pod(*it, &pod);
            int rc = cb(user_data, &pod);
            if (rc != 0) return 1;                  // user aborted early
        }
        return 0;                                    // success
    } catch (const blocksci::BlocksciError &) {
        return 2;                                    // chain open / read error
    } catch (...) {
        return 3;                                    // unknown failure
    }
}

/* --------------------------------------------------------------------
   End of C++ implementation
   -------------------------------------------------------------------- */
#endif /* __cplusplus */

/* =====================================================================
   Example usage from a pure C program (not compiled into the library)
   ===================================================================== */
/*
#include "blocksci_c.h"
#include <stdio.h>

static int count_cb(void *user, const bsci_block_t *blk) {
    size_t *cnt = (size_t *)user;
    (*cnt)++;
    // Example: stop after 10 million blocks (just to show early abort)
    if (*cnt == 10000000) return 1;
    return 0;
}

int main(void) {
    const char *chain_path = "/home/user/.bitcoin/blocksci";
    size_t nblocks = 0;
    int rc = bsci_foreach_block(chain_path, &nblocks, count_cb);
    if (rc) {
        fprintf(stderr, "Iteration stopped with error code %d (or early abort)\n", rc);
    }
    printf("Iterated over %zu blocks\n", nblocks);
    return 0;
}
*/

#endif /* BLOCKSCI_C_H */
```

### How it works

| Step | What happens | Why it stays fast |
|------|--------------|-------------------|
| **Create iterator** (`bsci_iter_create`) | Constructs a `blocksci::Chain` (opens the DB) and stores `begin()/end()` iterators. | Done once, outside the hot loop. |
| **Iterate** (`bsci_iter_next` or `bsci_foreach_block`) | A plain `for` loop over the native C++ iterator. For each block we fill a tiny POD (`bsci_block_t`) and call the user’s `bsci_block_cb_t`. | No virtual dispatch, no heap allocation, no `std::function`. The callback is a raw C function pointer – the compiler can inline the call if the pointer is known at compile‑time. |
| **Callback** | Receives a pointer to the POD (by const pointer) and a `void*` user context. Returns 0 to keep walking, non‑zero to abort. | The callback runs in the same thread, same stack; the only overhead is the function call itself. |
| **Error handling** | All C++ exceptions are caught inside the wrapper and turned into small integer error codes. | Guarantees a clean C ABI – no uncaught C++ exceptions crossing the boundary. |
| **Zero‑allocation** | The POD is allocated on the stack of the iteration function; no dynamic memory per block. | Keeps the hot path allocation‑free. |
| **Thread‑safety** | The iterator object is not shared; each thread must create its own iterator. | No hidden locks, no contention. |

### Compiling

```bash
# Build the binding as a shared library (example with clang++)
clang++ -std=c++20 -fPIC -shared -O3 -I/path/to/blocksci/include \
        -L/path/to/blocksci/lib -lblocksci \
        -o libblocksci_c.so blocksci_c.h   # the file is both header & impl
```

Link a C program against `-lblocksci_c` (or just compile the header into the program if you prefer a static build).

### Extending the POD

If you need more block fields (e.g. merkle root, block hash, etc.):

1. Add the new members to `bsci_block_t` **before** any existing members (to preserve layout for existing callers).  
2. Extend `fill_block_pod()` to copy the data.  
3. Re‑compile the library; the ABI remains compatible because the struct stays POD and its size only grows.

---

That’s the complete, ready‑to‑drop‑in binding. The hot path (`bsci_foreach_block`) is a tight, allocation‑free loop that calls a plain C function pointer for each of the ~800 million blocks, giving C users the same ergonomic “per‑row” experience that pandas/Polars provide while keeping BlockSci’s native C++ performance.
